<br>
Do we all agree that debates have to be based on logic, facts and data? or we do include 'opinion' debates? <br>
<br>
I will be the first to admit, I am a kinesthetic person. (and at the risk of this being taken out of context and turned on me in jest) I &quot;feel&quot; alot more than more that I  &quot;think&quot; through things. I go with my gut and heart over data.  I think data can be twisted, and Its like my 6th sense analyzes things more quickly than my conscious thought.<br>
<br>
At work we have been studying different personality types.  I think that these differences are very ingrained in us and are not necessarily right or wrong.  Not saying we cant change things about ourselves, but I think that we are just wired differently in some things.<br>
<br>
Ok I am rambling.......<br>
The question really is, why or why not??? Opinions vs. hard data when we are debating here. - Shirene <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gaia25>Gaia25</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 265<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/4/03 4:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=199.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Debate Board, fact or opinion???</span><hr size=1> I do think that some people are wired for religion and others aren't.  I don't think the use of feelings is redundant in a debate..but at the same time, I don't think that feelings will be given the same amount of &quot;respect&quot; (not sure if thats the right word) as facts are KWIM? <p><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:blue;font-family:comic sans ms;font-size:medium;">There's no such thing as Rock 'n' Roll Faeries - Rhiannon, aged 7</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=doublelatte>Double Latte</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Got Milk?</span><br>  Posts: 151<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/4/03 10:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=199.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Debate Board, fact or opinion???</span><hr size=1> Well, it's not a support board and it's a relief not to be held to Babycenter's touchy-feely standards. Nobody's selling Charmin here so we don't need to worry about scaring people away. However, I like a lot of the people here and wouldn't deliberately choose to be offensive (unless responding to Michael the Theist<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
<br>
I partly agree with Shirene's comment about facts sometimes being twisted to suit an argument. Last night on the news they were carrying on about SARS -saying it's &quot;Severe Acute Media Syndrome&quot; and how chances are so much greater that you will get AIDS. Statistically true, but SARS is scary because it's new, unlike AIDS it can be contracted through very casual contact (such sharing a plane ride) and can result in death rather quickly. So the statistic of AIDS versus SARS is not a reasonable comparison proves nothing. <br>
<br>
However, I think where statistics fail we need to apply logic and common sense over &quot;feelings.&quot;<br>
<br>
DL<br>
<br>
 <p>&quot;Beware of a clear and present evil in the name of some future, nebulous good.&quot;</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 373<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/4/03 7:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=199.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   re: Debate vs. Support</span><hr size=1> The rules of any board are usually laid out by the moderator or creator, and I think Em was pretty clear that this is a debate board (as opposed to BC where we were mostly from support boards), but that she has no other rules. On some other boards they are very finicky about language and proper placement of posts in the relevant threads etc. If this were to go the way of an opinion and friendship circle board, I'd probably opt out since BC does that for me and I get my fill of restrictions there.<br>
<br>
The dictionary defines debate as:<br>
<br>
&quot;a contention by words or arguments: as a : the formal discussion of a motion before a deliberative body according to the rules of parliamentary procedure b : a regulated discussion of a proposition between two matched sides&quot;<br>
<br>
Debate is about logic, evidence and reasoned argument. If you are looking for a place to prosyletize, share experience or receive spiritual guidance, I'd say you're on the wrong board and I think if you want to use gut reactions and &quot;6th sense&quot; arguments you can try, but will always fall short on a debate board where reason and logic are the most basic regulating principles.<br>
<br>
That said, you are absolutely correct--data can be twisted or at least interpreted many ways (see any macroeconomics book--weeee), but that's where the heart of debate lies. Feeling will not clarify data, and is generally not appropriate in formal debate (she says right after admitting the FU post was out of line in a debate setting)<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
P.S. We don't have real formal debates where one person on each side takes on a topic and responds one at a time point for point, but it would be fun. Same rules and guidelines apply though.<br>
<br>
<br>
