<br>
We've read some persuasive arguments and analyzed them.  We've been trying to come up with a formula of sorts for an effective persuasive argument.  We've come to the conclusion that it all depends on your audience, but that a good mix of logical appeals and emotional appeals are a must.  <br>
<br>
I think that emotional appeals/opinions/etc are entirely appropriate in persuasion.  However, I do not view a debate as the same as persuasion.  I think that they have different purposes.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 377<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/15/03 12:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=199.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   re: hehehe</span><hr size=1> &quot;You can claim men are better breast-feeders than women...&quot;<br>
